// src/data/testsData.en.js — English hard-style test questions
const testsDataEN = {
  1: [
    { id:1, question:"A website displays HTTPS and a padlock in the address bar. What does this guarantee?", options:["The site is safe and cannot be fraudulent","The connection is encrypted, but not the authenticity of the site owner","User data is not collected","The site has been verified by an antivirus company"], correct:1, explanation:"HTTPS only guarantees channel encryption — no one intercepts the traffic. But the site itself can be a phishing page: fraudsters also obtain SSL certificates. Over 80% of phishing sites use HTTPS. The padlock is not a trust seal for the site owner." },
    { id:2, question:"A friend sent you a sensational headline: 'Proven: GMOs cause cancer!' with a link to health-truth24.ru. What do you do FIRST?", options:["Share it — if my friend sent it, they must have checked it","Find the primary source: was this research published in a peer-reviewed journal?","Check whether the site has HTTPS — that means it's reliable","See how many times the article has already been shared"], correct:1, explanation:"Share count and sender trust are poor indicators of truthfulness. Misinformation spreads 6× faster than truth. The primary source is a peer-reviewed article (PubMed, Lancet, Nature). A two-word domain with a number is a clear sign of an unreliable source." },
    { id:3, question:"Which of the following is NOT part of your digital footprint?", options:["Your Google search history","The serial number of your CPU","A geotagged photo published on Instagram","A comment you deleted a year ago"], correct:1, explanation:"Your CPU serial number is never automatically published. Everything else is part of your digital footprint: searches are stored by Google, geotags are embedded in photo EXIF data, and deleted comments are often cached on Wayback Machine or in screenshots." },
    { id:4, question:"You discover a flashlight app on Android requesting access to contacts, microphone, and location. What principle does this violate?", options:["Zero Trust principle","Data Minimization principle","Defense in Depth principle","Least Privilege principle"], correct:1, explanation:"Data minimization requires collecting only what is strictly necessary for the service's function. A flashlight only needs access to the camera flash. Requesting contacts, microphone, and location is excessive data collection, often monetized through ad networks." },
    { id:5, question:"'95% of cyberattacks begin with human error.' What conclusion is most accurate?", options:["Technical security tools are useless — everything depends on people","Antivirus and firewalls aren't needed if users are well-trained","User training is a critical security layer alongside technical measures","The human factor can be completely eliminated through automation"], correct:2, explanation:"The statistic highlights the importance of the human factor, not the uselessness of technology. The correct conclusion: protection must be multi-layered (defense in depth). Training alone without technology, or technology alone without training, is incomplete. Automation reduces risk but doesn't eliminate it." },
  ],
  2: [
    { id:1, question:"After registration, a site emails you your password in plain text. What does this mean?", options:["The site uses strong encryption — otherwise how could it send it?","The password is stored in unencrypted or reversibly encrypted form — this is a serious security flaw","It's standard practice — for account recovery","Two-factor authentication compensates for this risk"], correct:1, explanation:"If a site can send you your password, it's stored in readable form (plaintext or reversible encryption). The correct practice: store only password hashes (bcrypt, Argon2). In a breach, all passwords on such a site end up with attackers. Change that password immediately and never reuse it." },
    { id:2, question:"Which of these passwords has the greatest entropy (hardest to brute-force)?", options:["P@ssw0rd!2024","qK#9mX$vL2@nW","correct-horse-battery-staple-2024","MyVery_LongPassword!"], correct:2, explanation:"A passphrase of random words has high entropy due to length (35+ characters). qK#9m... looks complex but is short. P@ssw0rd is a predictable leet-speak substitution pattern already in all dictionaries. Password length matters more than character complexity: each extra character increases combinations exponentially." },
    { id:3, question:"A colleague says: 'I use SMS 2FA, so my password doesn't matter — I can use a simple one.' Is he right?", options:["Yes — 2FA fully compensates for a weak password","No — SIM-swapping and SMS interception make SMS 2FA vulnerable; the password still matters","Partly — if biometrics are enabled, the password doesn't matter","Yes — with 2FA, the password is just a formality"], correct:1, explanation:"SMS 2FA has vulnerabilities: SIM swapping (an attacker ports your number to their SIM), SS7 protocol attacks on carrier networks, SMS interception via malware. A weak password makes the first factor easier to attack. The ideal: strong password + hardware key (YubiKey) or TOTP app (Google Authenticator) instead of SMS." },
    { id:4, question:"You've forgotten your password manager's master password. What happens?", options:["Support can reset it via email","You can recover using biometrics on your phone","Access to the vault is lost — most managers cannot decrypt data without the master password","Passwords can be exported as a backup without the master password"], correct:2, explanation:"Good password managers (Bitwarden, 1Password) use zero-knowledge architecture: they don't know your master password. Decryption happens only on the user's device. This means nobody — including support — can recover access. Write your master password on paper and store it in a safe physical location." },
    { id:5, question:"Which type of two-factor authentication is most resistant to phishing?", options:["SMS code to your phone","TOTP code from an app (Google Authenticator)","Hardware security key (FIDO2/WebAuthn)","Code sent to your email"], correct:2, explanation:"FIDO2/WebAuthn (YubiKey, Titan Key) uses public-key cryptography and is bound to a specific domain. Even if you enter it on a phishing site — the key won't work because the domain doesn't match. SMS and email can be intercepted or forwarded. TOTP codes can be entered on a phishing site in real time. A hardware key is the only method with built-in anti-phishing protection." },
  ],
  3: [
    { id:1, question:"You receive an email from 'security@google.com' about suspicious activity. The address looks exactly correct. What do you check FIRST?", options:["Click 'Review Activity' — the link is safe if the domain is right","Open Google directly in your browser and check account security in settings","Check whether the link in the email uses HTTPS","Reply to the email and ask for identity confirmation"], correct:1, explanation:"Sender addresses can be spoofed (email spoofing). The safe approach: don't click links in the email — open the site manually. Legitimate Google security notifications will also appear at accounts.google.com. Replying to the attacker only confirms your account is active." },
    { id:2, question:"How does spear phishing fundamentally differ from regular phishing?", options:["It uses only voice calls, not email","It targets a specific person using their personal data, making it far more convincing","It only attacks corporate networks, not individuals","It's technically more complex — it requires hacking the mail server"], correct:1, explanation:"Spear phishing is a personalized attack. The attacker researches the victim first: colleague names, ongoing projects, writing style, bank name. The email contains real details ('Hi Sarah, regarding the Almaty_Q4 project, I need your signature...'). Spear phishing succeeds 3× more often than generic phishing. This is how Ubiquiti lost $46.7M." },
    { id:3, question:"What is 'pretexting' in social engineering?", options:["Creating a fake site with a similar domain name","Sending mass phishing emails without personalization","Inventing a believable cover story and false identity to manipulate a victim","Technically scanning for vulnerabilities before an attack"], correct:2, explanation:"Pretexting is the creation of a scenario (pretext): 'I'm from IT support, I need your password to update the system' or 'I'm a bank auditor, tell me the last 4 digits of your card.' The attacker creates a plausible role and situation that lowers the victim's guard. This is a purely psychological attack requiring no technical tools." },
    { id:4, question:"You receive an email with an attachment named 'Report_Q3_2024.pdf.exe'. What has happened?", options:["It's a corrupted PDF — open it and re-save","It's a double extension — a hidden executable disguised as a PDF","Windows will automatically block the execution of such a file","The file is safe if the sender is someone you know"], correct:1, explanation:"A double extension (.pdf.exe) is a classic trick. Windows hides known extensions by default, so the user sees 'Report_Q3_2024.pdf' and assumes it's a document. In reality, an .exe file gets executed. Windows does not block such files automatically. Never run .exe files from emails — even from known contacts who may be compromised." },
    { id:5, question:"What is typosquatting and why is it dangerous?", options:["Password theft via DNS request interception","Registering domains with misspellings of popular sites to catch mistyping users","Injecting malicious code into a legitimate site via SQL injection","Using browser autofill to steal passwords"], correct:1, explanation:"Typosquatting: fraudsters register 'goggle.com', 'amaz0n.com', 'app1e.com' — domains users land on when they mistype. The site looks identical to the original and collects credentials. The risk increases on mobile devices where small fonts make URL verification harder. Always use bookmarks for critical sites." },
  ],
  4: [
    { id:1, question:"An attacker wants to target you via social media OSINT. Which combination of data from public sources is most valuable?", options:["Name and favorite movie from VK","Full name + employer + bank + date of birth from various public posts","Follower count and public likes","Profile picture and username"], correct:1, explanation:"The attacker needs a data combination for social engineering: knowing your name, bank, and date of birth, they can call the bank, impersonate you, and request account changes. LinkedIn gives title and company, Instagram gives bank (card photos, office interior), Facebook gives date of birth. This is how loans are taken out in someone else's name." },
    { id:2, question:"You signed into a new app via 'Continue with Facebook'. What happened from a security perspective?", options:["Nothing — it's safer than creating a separate password","The app received an OAuth token and can read your Facebook profile data per the requested permissions","Facebook sent the app your password in encrypted form","A separate isolated account was created, unlinked to Facebook"], correct:1, explanation:"OAuth doesn't transfer your password, but issues an access token for profile data. The scope of data depends on requested permissions: name and email is the minimum, contacts and posts is the maximum. If the app is breached, the attacker gets this token. Additionally, compromising your Facebook account loses access to all services authenticated through it." },
    { id:3, question:"What is credential stuffing and how does it differ from brute-force?", options:["They're the same — automated password guessing","Credential stuffing tests real login/password pairs from breaches on other sites; brute-force tries all possible combinations","Credential stuffing only attacks corporate systems","Brute-force uses dictionaries; credential stuffing uses random combinations"], correct:1, explanation:"Credential stuffing uses databases of stolen credentials (bought on darknet markets) and automatically tests them on hundreds of sites. This works because 65% of users repeat passwords. Brute-force tries every possible combination. Credential stuffing is far more efficient: a 0.1–2% success rate from a billion pairs = thousands of cracked accounts." },
    { id:4, question:"Which action IMMEDIATELY reduces your OSINT exposure on social media?", options:["Change your username to a pseudonym","Switch profiles to private and remove excessive personal data from descriptions","Delete all posts older than a year","Turn off location on your phone"], correct:1, explanation:"Changing your username doesn't help — all old posts with tags and mentions remain. Private mode restricts strangers' access to content. Removing your real name, employer, phone, and ID number from the public description eliminates key OSINT data. Turning off phone location doesn't affect already-published data." },
    { id:5, question:"You notice an unfamiliar device in Facebook's 'Active Sessions' section. What is the correct order of actions?", options:["Delete Facebook and create a new account","End all sessions → change password → enable 2FA → review security settings and connected apps","Change the password first, then end the attacker's sessions","Wait — it's probably just an old device"], correct:1, explanation:"The order is critical: end sessions first — otherwise the attacker retains access even after a password change via the active session token. Then change the password + enable 2FA. Notify contacts later, when the account is under control. Deleting the account means losing recovery access for all accounts tied to that email." },
  ],
  5: [
    { id:1, question:"How does a rootkit fundamentally differ from a regular virus?", options:["A rootkit encrypts files; a virus deletes them","Rootkits only run on Linux systems","A rootkit hides itself at the OS kernel level, making detection extremely difficult","Rootkits spread only via USB drives"], correct:2, explanation:"A rootkit embeds into the OS kernel or bootloader and conceals itself: hiding processes, files, and network connections from antivirus and the user. The system 'looks clean' but is infected. Detecting a rootkit with a standard antivirus is difficult — you need to boot from a clean medium or use specialized tools (Rootkit Revealer, GMER)." },
    { id:2, question:"Your computer is idle but the CPU is at 90–100% and the fan is running at maximum. What might this indicate?", options:["This is normal — Windows is updating in the background","The hard drive has overheated","The device may be infected with a cryptominer using your computing resources","There isn't enough RAM"], correct:2, explanation:"Cryptominers (coinminers) are malware that secretly use the CPU/GPU to mine cryptocurrency. Symptoms: high idle load, overheating, slow performance. Check Task Manager for suspicious high-CPU processes. An antivirus scan and checking startup programs will help identify the threat." },
    { id:3, question:"Why might a standard backup not save you from ransomware?", options:["Ransomware physically deletes all backup files","If the backup is connected to the infected system, it will also be encrypted","Antivirus blocks restore from backup","Backup only works for documents, not system files"], correct:1, explanation:"Modern ransomware scans and encrypts connected drives, network shares, and cloud storage with sync enabled. If an external drive is plugged in — it gets encrypted too. The 3-2-1 rule solves this: one copy must be offline (disconnected from the system) or in a cloud without direct sync. That's why backups must be kept isolated." },
    { id:4, question:"What is 'fileless malware' and why is it more dangerous than regular malware?", options:["Malware without an icon — detected only by file size","Malware operating in RAM and legitimate system processes without writing files to disk","Malware that only spreads via email without attachments","Malware that self-destructs after first execution"], correct:1, explanation:"Fileless malware executes in memory (PowerShell, WMI, registry) and creates no files on disk — a file-scanning antivirus won't detect it. It uses legitimate system tools (living-off-the-land). Evidence disappears after a reboot. Detection requires behavioral analysis and EDR solutions, not signature-based antivirus." },
    { id:5, question:"You opened a PDF from someone you know — nothing happened and the file looks normal. Should you be concerned?", options:["No — if the document opened correctly, there's no threat","No — PDFs can't contain executable code","Yes — a malicious PDF can exploit a vulnerability in the reader and execute code silently","Yes, only if the PDF contains macros like Word documents"], correct:2, explanation:"PDFs support JavaScript and embedded objects, and can exploit vulnerabilities in Adobe Reader or browser-based viewers. Malicious code can execute without any visible signs. If your contact's account was compromised, they may unknowingly be spreading malware. Suspicious PDFs should be checked on VirusTotal or opened in an isolated environment." },
  ],
  6: [
    { id:1, question:"You visit your bank's website over public Wi-Fi and see HTTPS. Are you protected from a MITM attack?", options:["Yes — HTTPS fully protects against interception on a public network","Not necessarily — an SSL-stripping attack can silently downgrade the connection to HTTP","Yes — banks use additional encryption on top of HTTPS","No — HTTPS provides no protection against MITM at all"], correct:1, explanation:"SSL stripping: an MITM attacker intercepts the unencrypted request before an HTTPS connection is established and substitutes https:// with http://. The victim sees the site without a padlock and doesn't notice. Protection: HSTS (HTTP Strict Transport Security) — the browser remembers that this domain is always HTTPS. But the first request is still vulnerable without a VPN." },
    { id:2, question:"Why is an Evil Twin attack so effective?", options:["The attacker cracks the password of the legitimate access point","Devices automatically connect to the network with the strongest signal, even if it's fake","Evil Twin exploits a WPA3 vulnerability to decrypt traffic","The victim receives a warning but usually ignores it"], correct:1, explanation:"Devices remember network names (SSIDs) and automatically reconnect to familiar ones. Evil Twin uses the same SSID as the legitimate network but with a stronger signal — the device switches automatically. No password is needed for open networks. The victim receives no warnings. Disable 'auto-connect' in your Wi-Fi settings." },
    { id:3, question:"You urgently need to check your bank account while at a café. What is the safest approach?", options:["Connect to the café's Wi-Fi and enable a VPN","Use mobile data (4G/5G) without Wi-Fi","Connect to the café's official Wi-Fi — it has a password, so it's secure","Open an incognito browser window — it hides your traffic from others"], correct:1, explanation:"Mobile data (4G/5G) is the safest option: other devices at the café have no access to it. A VPN on public Wi-Fi encrypts traffic but the Wi-Fi network itself remains a risk point. A Wi-Fi password doesn't protect you from traffic interception by other users on the same network. Incognito mode doesn't hide traffic — it only avoids saving browser history." },
    { id:4, question:"Why is WEP Wi-Fi encryption considered broken and dangerous?", options:["WEP uses the outdated MD5 algorithm, which is easily decoded","WEP keys are too short and can be brute-forced in hours","WEP has a cryptographic flaw in its IV (initialization vector): passive packet capture allows the key to be cracked in minutes","WEP is not supported by devices newer than 2005"], correct:2, explanation:"WEP uses RC4 with a 24-bit IV that periodically repeats. An attacker passively collects packets and statistically recovers the key. Tools like aircrack-ng crack WEP in 1–5 minutes with sufficient traffic. WEP was discredited as early as 2001. Use only WPA2 or WPA3." },
    { id:5, question:"What makes the 'auto-connect to Wi-Fi' feature on your phone dangerous?", options:["It drains the battery faster","The phone may connect to an Evil Twin or random open network without the user's knowledge","It broadcasts the device's MAC address to all nearby networks","Only open networks are affected — password-protected networks are safe"], correct:1, explanation:"The phone stores a list of 'trusted' networks by SSID and automatically connects to any network with a matching name. 'Airport_WiFi' is easy to spoof. The device connects automatically and all traffic passes through the attacker. Disable auto-connect for all public networks and keep only your home Wi-Fi enabled." },
  ],
  7: [
    { id:1, question:"Equifax didn't install an Apache Struts patch for two months and lost 147 million people's data. What conclusion is MOST accurate?", options:["Companies shouldn't use third-party libraries (Apache Struts)","Critical security patches require immediate testing and deployment — the window between patch release and installation is actively exploited","The breach was unavoidable — zero-day vulnerabilities are always exploited","The problem was that Equifax wasn't using antivirus"], correct:1, explanation:"The CVE-2017-5638 vulnerability was publicly known and the patch was available. Equifax knew about the vulnerability but failed to install the fix. Average time from patch release to mass exploitation: 14 days. Attackers actively monitor CVE databases. The absence of a patch management process for a known critical vulnerability is direct negligence." },
    { id:2, question:"What makes a zero-day vulnerability especially dangerous compared to a regular one?", options:["Its exploit is harder to write","There's no patch — the software vendor doesn't yet know about it or hasn't had time to release a fix","It only affects zero-day updated software versions","It requires physical access to the device"], correct:1, explanation:"'Zero-day' means zero days of response time for the developer. With no patch, there's no technical defense. Antivirus misses it, firewalls don't block it — the vulnerability isn't documented yet. The only mitigations: least privilege principle, network segmentation, behavioral EDR systems. Zero-day exploits sell on the market for hundreds of thousands of dollars." },
    { id:3, question:"Your router vendor announces End-of-Life (EOL) — end of support. What does this mean in practice?", options:["The router will stop working in 30 days","The device will no longer receive security updates — new vulnerabilities will never be patched","Internet speed will decrease due to outdated firmware","The device warranty expires"], correct:1, explanation:"EOL means: the vendor no longer releases patches. All vulnerabilities discovered after EOL will remain unpatched forever. A router with EOL firmware is a permanently widening hole in your home network's security. Replacing the device isn't an option — it's a necessity. The same applies to Windows XP, Android 8, and other EOL systems." },
    { id:4, question:"Why can Microsoft's 'Patch Tuesday' create risk?", options:["Updates sometimes introduce new bugs and require testing before enterprise deployment","Microsoft deliberately slows down computers through updates","Patches come too frequently — IT teams can't keep up","Tuesday updates require a reboot during business hours"], correct:0, explanation:"The patching paradox in enterprise: major updates can break critical systems (ERP, medical equipment, industrial controllers). So organizations follow a patch management process: test in a staging environment → deploy in waves → monitor. The risk isn't in the updates themselves but in deploying them immediately without testing." },
    { id:5, question:"You see a pop-up: 'Update Java now!' with an 'Update' button. What is the safest action?", options:["Click 'Update' — you should install updates immediately","Close the window, go to the official java.com site, and check for updates there","Check if the window has the Java logo — if so, it's safe","Click 'Remind me later' — that's safer"], correct:1, explanation:"Pop-ups demanding you update Java, Flash, or your browser are a classic malware delivery method. Legitimate software updates through built-in mechanisms or official sites. Never click 'Update' in a browser pop-up window. Logos can be copied easily. Close the window and manually check for updates via Settings or the official site." },
  ],
  8: [
    { id:1, question:"A company claims it 'anonymized' data by removing usernames. Why is this insufficient?", options:["A name is the only identifying element — removing it provides anonymity","A combination of other attributes (age, gender, location, purchases) allows most records to be re-identified","This is sufficient under GDPR requirements","It's sufficient only for social media data, not medical data"], correct:1, explanation:"Latanya Sweeney's research (MIT): knowing ZIP code, date of birth, and gender allows you to identify 87% of Americans. Netflix 'anonymized' viewing data — researchers de-anonymized it by cross-referencing with public IMDb ratings. True anonymization (k-anonymity, differential privacy) requires specialized methods, not just name removal." },
    { id:2, question:"What is browser fingerprinting and why is it hard to block?", options:["Passwords saved by the browser — turned off in settings","A unique combination of browser characteristics (version, plugins, screen resolution, fonts) allowing you to be tracked without cookies","Biometric identification via webcam","An outdated technology replaced by localStorage"], correct:1, explanation:"A browser fingerprint is created from hundreds of parameters: browser version, OS, installed fonts, WebGL rendering, screen resolution, time zone. The combination is unique for 90%+ of devices. Blocking cookies doesn't help. Protection: Tor Browser (standardizes the fingerprint), Firefox with Privacy Resist Fingerprinting. Complete blocking is practically impossible." },
    { id:3, question:"The right to erasure (GDPR Art. 17) allows you to:", options:["Delete any information about yourself from any website in the world","Require a company to delete your personal data under certain conditions, if it's no longer needed for the original purpose","Force Google to remove search results about you in any case","Receive financial compensation for the use of your data"], correct:1, explanation:"The right to erasure is not absolute: a company can refuse if data is needed to fulfill a contract, for legal obligations, or for public interest. It applies only to companies handling EU residents' data. Google removes search results only from European versions of the search engine. Requests go to the DPA (supervisory authority) if the company refuses." },
    { id:4, question:"An app requests access to your microphone. What happens when you grant it?", options:["The app can only use the microphone when it's open on screen","Depends on the OS and permissions — in the worst case, background recording at any time without notification","The permission only applies to calls within the app","iOS and Android fully block background microphone access"], correct:1, explanation:"On Android before version 10, apps could access the microphone in the background. Modern OSes restrict background access, but malicious apps find workarounds. Even legitimate apps have been accused of recording keywords for ads (Facebook, TikTok). The principle: grant microphone access only to apps that clearly need it (calls, voice notes)." },
    { id:5, question:"Which browser setting provides the LEAST real protection against online tracking?", options:["Enabling the uBlock Origin extension","Incognito / private browsing mode","Enabling DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","Disabling JavaScript on untrusted sites"], correct:1, explanation:"Incognito mode only avoids saving history on your device. Your ISP, employer, and the sites you visit still see your traffic. Your IP address remains the same. Cookies aren't automatically blocked. Extensions like uBlock Origin, DoH, and JavaScript restrictions genuinely affect privacy. Incognito is protection from someone looking over your shoulder, not from tracking." },
  ],
  9: [
    { id:1, question:"You've discovered your email was hacked. What should you do FIRST?", options:["Message all contacts warning them not to open suspicious emails","End all active email account sessions, then change the password","Change the password first, then end the sessions","Delete the account and create a new one"], correct:1, explanation:"The order matters: end sessions first — otherwise the attacker retains access even after a password change via an active session token. Then change the password + enable 2FA. Notify contacts later, once the account is under control. Deleting the account means losing recovery access for all accounts tied to that email." },
    { id:2, question:"Why do experts recommend NOT paying ransomware ransoms?", options:["It violates the attackers' copyright","Payment doesn't guarantee decryption, funds the next attacks, and marks you as willing to pay","Cryptocurrency transfers are technically impossible for private individuals","The law prohibits paying criminals in most countries"], correct:1, explanation:"Statistics: about 40% of organizations that paid a ransom did not receive a working decryption key. Payment funds development of new attacks. Payers end up on 'blacklists' — they'll be targeted again. The right approach: 3-2-1 backups, isolate infected systems, report to the FBI/police (free decryptors sometimes exist at nomoreransom.org)." },
    { id:3, question:"What does the 'average breach detection time of 207 days' (IBM) mean?", options:["Companies detect a breach 207 days after it's been remediated","On average, an attacker has undetected access to the victim's systems for 207 days","207 days is the standard cybercrime investigation timeline","In 207 days, hackers manage to breach 207 systems"], correct:1, explanation:"207 days is the 'dwell time': the attacker infiltrates the network and goes undetected for nearly 7 months. During this time they study the infrastructure, expand access, and steal data. Early detection is critical: every day of delay increases damage. This is why anomaly monitoring (SIEM) is needed, not just perimeter defense." },
    { id:4, question:"You notice three small charges of $1–5 from an unknown company on your card. What might this indicate?", options:["The bank is running test transactions to verify the card","Fraudsters are testing stolen card data before a larger theft","It's an accidentally set up subscription — cancel it in the app","A bank technical glitch — the money will be refunded automatically"], correct:1, explanation:"Small 'test' transactions are a classic scheme: fraudsters check whether a stolen card works and whether fraud monitoring is active. If all is quiet, a large charge follows. Act immediately: block the card, report fraud to your bank, and request a chargeback. Don't wait — any delay increases the risk of major losses." },
    { id:5, question:"After discovering a breach, you want to reboot the infected computer. What might this destroy?", options:["Only temporary files from the %TEMP% folder","Active processes in RAM — including attack traces and evidence needed for an investigation","Nothing important — all attacker traces are already on disk","Only files open at the moment of the attack"], correct:1, explanation:"Digital forensics requires preserving the system state: a RAM image (RAM dump) can contain encryption keys, active malware processes, and network connections. Rebooting destroys this data permanently. In a serious incident: don't power off the device before a specialist arrives or before capturing a memory image (Volatility, FTK Imager)." },
  ],
  10: [
    { id:1, question:"The Principle of Least Privilege means:", options:["Users should not have the administrator password","Each system subject receives only the minimum rights needed to perform their specific task","Privileges should be held by the least experienced employees","All users have equal rights for fairness"], correct:1, explanation:"Least Privilege limits the blast radius of a compromise: a breached accountant's account shouldn't have access to source code. If malware runs under a regular user, it can't install a rootkit without admin rights. Applied to users, processes, services, and APIs. Violating this principle is one of the causes of large-scale breaches." },
    { id:2, question:"You used a strong, unique password and 2FA on a site. The site was hacked and the database published. What happened to your protection?", options:["You're completely unprotected — change the password everywhere immediately","Your password was securely hashed (if the site did it right) and 2FA additionally protects the account","2FA became useless after the database leaked","A unique password doesn't matter — in a DB breach the attacker gets direct access"], correct:1, explanation:"If the site stored passwords correctly (bcrypt, Argon2 with salt), the attacker only got hashes — cracking them takes years or is impossible. A unique password prevents credential stuffing on other sites. 2FA requires physical access to the second factor. Conclusion: your account on that site is at risk, others are not. Still worth changing the password on that specific site." },
    { id:3, question:"What does the concept of 'Zero Trust Architecture' mean?", options:["Don't trust any users — delete their accounts at the slightest suspicion","Verify every access request as if it came from a hostile network — even within corporate infrastructure","Only trust open-source solutions — not proprietary software","Disconnect all external connections and work offline only"], correct:1, explanation:"Zero Trust abandons the 'perimeter' model: inside the network is safe, outside is dangerous. If a VPN or internal device is compromised, the attacker gets full access. Zero Trust: every request is independently verified regardless of origin. Principles: explicit verification + least privilege + assume breach. Google has used this (BeyondCorp) since 2009." },
    { id:4, question:"Which combination of tools provides the MOST comprehensive account protection?", options:["Complex password + SMS 2FA + antivirus","Unique long password + FIDO2 hardware key + password manager","Biometrics + PIN code + VPN","Two-factor authentication + frequent password changes + incognito mode"], correct:1, explanation:"A unique long password prevents credential stuffing and brute-force. A password manager ensures its uniqueness and complexity. A FIDO2 hardware key is the only 2FA method completely resistant to phishing (domain-bound). SMS is vulnerable to SIM-swapping. Frequent password changes without a manager lead to weaker passwords. Antivirus and VPN are important but not for account security specifically." },
    { id:5, question:"Your threat model should answer the question:", options:["'How do I protect myself from all possible cyberattacks simultaneously?'","'Who might want to attack me, what do they want, and what measures are proportionate to that risk?'","'Which antivirus ranks highest on AV-TEST?'","'How much does comprehensive cybersecurity cost and can I afford it?'"], correct:1, explanation:"Threat modeling is individual risk assessment. A journalist protects sources from state actors. An entrepreneur protects financial data from fraudsters. A regular user protects against automated attacks and phishing. Different threats require different measures: paranoid protection everywhere is irrational, but no baseline protection is dangerous. Start with: 'Who am I interesting to and what can they do?'" },
  ],
};

export default testsDataEN;
